== The claim ==

In the [[Psi Field]] Lagrangian, the source term is <math>J_\psi</math>. The hypothesis states:

<math>J_\psi(x, t) = \beta \cdot \Phi(x, t)</math>

where Φ(x, t) is an '''intention density''' — a coarse-grained measure of how much coherent attention is currently directed at the point (x, t) by all observers — and β is a coupling constant (currently undetermined; framework estimates β ~ 10⁻⁴⁰ in natural units, well below current experimental sensitivity for laboratory-scale Φ).

A higher intention density at (x, t) yields a stronger local ψ amplitude, which (through the <math>\alpha F_{\mu\nu}F^{\mu\nu}</math> vertex) is hypothesised to produce small but measurable EM signatures.

== Operationalising intention ==

Intention density is unobservable directly but has proposed proxies:

* '''Number of attending observers''' (e.g. a meditation group focused on a single object).
* '''Quality of attention''' indexed by [[Resonant Neurobiology]] markers (alpha coherence, HRV).
* '''Duration sustained''' — exponentially weighted by recent history.

A useful operational definition for the [[Psi Recorder]] and [[Psi Tether]]:

<math>\Phi_{\text{eff}} = \sum_i w_i(t) \cdot C_i(t)</math>

over operators i, where C_i is operator i's instantaneous coherence score (cardio-respiratory or alpha) and w_i is a participation weight.

== Predictions ==

# A larger coherent group (more operators above coherence threshold) should produce a larger measurable ψ-coupled EM signature than the same operators uncoordinated.
# Pre-registered group-coherence tasks should show effect sizes scaling with group size and coherence — testable via PEAR-style random-event-generator deviation experiments.
# The [[Resonant Hailer]] and [[Coherence Beacon]] should produce larger downstream effects in operator cohorts than equivalent random EM emission.

All three predictions are unverified at production confidence; the second has historical PEAR-lineage support that has not been independently replicated to mainstream standard.

== Distinction from "wishful thinking" ==

The framework's claim is '''not''' that wishing makes things happen. The claim is that '''coherent attention generates a real (if small) field perturbation''', which has the same operational status as gravitational waves before LIGO: predicted by formalism, undetected at current sensitivity, falsifiable.

Operators are explicitly cautioned: '''Mk0–Mk1 Psi-Tech does not amplify intention to macroscopic effect.''' Any subjective experience of efficacy in current devices is best explained by ritual, placebo, and group-coherence wellbeing effects — themselves real and valuable, but not "thoughts moving matter".

